- [x] avoid or workaround localStorage quota (even by compression if needed) â€” the actual quota risk was always the highscore board's optional replay payload (can run into the megabytes for a long multi-level run), which previously only got *reacted* to (dropping replay data and retrying) after a `setItem` already threw. New `src/engine/storageCompression.ts` gzip-compresses (`CompressionStream`/`DecompressionStream`, base64-encoded for storage) whatever gets written under the `codeenstein-highscores` key *before* that cascade ever runs, falling back to plain JSON if compression isn't smaller (tiny boards) or isn't supported at all â€” no new npm dependency, per this project's "keep dependencies minimal" rule, same reasoning as using `crypto.subtle.digest` for the AST hash instead of a bundled hash library. A `"gz1:"` prefix distinguishes compressed values from every already-stored plain-JSON board, so existing players' data keeps loading unchanged. `loadHighscores`/`recordHighscore` are now `async` to accommodate this; the pre-existing drop-replay cascade is otherwise untouched and still serves as the last-resort fallback for boards that don't fit even compressed. Campaign save/gore/difficulty/volume keys were left alone â€” small fixed-shape values with no realistic quota risk, where gzip+base64 overhead would likely make them bigger, not smaller. Verified in headless Chromium against the real module: small objects round-trip and correctly skip compression (no size win), a large synthetic replay-bearing entry round-trips byte-for-byte and compresses meaningfully smaller, a legacy uncompressed board already in `localStorage` still loads correctly, and â€” with `localStorage.setItem` temporarily wrapped to simulate a small quota â€” compression alone now saves a board that previously would've needed its replay dropped, while the drop-replay cascade still correctly kicks in once even compressed data doesn't fit
