- [x] canvas should fill as much of the window as possible while keeping aspect ratio â€” the canvas was capped at `width: min(100%, 960px)`, a fixed max-width that left a lot of a wide monitor unused. Tried a pure-CSS `width:auto; height:auto; max-width:100%; max-height:100%; aspect-ratio:640/400;` fix first and it didn't work: `width:auto` on a replaced element like `<canvas>` falls back to its *intrinsic* size (the 640Ă—400 `width`/`height` attributes) rather than growing to fill available space â€” `max-width`/`max-height` only ever let it *shrink*, never grow, so the canvas stayed pinned at ~640Ă—400 regardless of window size. Replaced with a JS-driven fit: the canvas is now wrapped in a new `canvasArea` flex-grow `<div>` (absorbs whatever vertical space `#viewport`'s other children â€” hint caption, controls legend, replay transport bar â€” don't need) and a `fitCanvasToArea()` function in `main.ts` reads `canvasArea`'s actual content-box size and sets the canvas's inline `width`/`height` in px to the largest 640:400 box that fits inside it, wired up via a `ResizeObserver` on `canvasArea` (fires automatically on window resizes *and* on `canvasArea.hidden` flipping false at a level launch â€” no explicit call needed at each call site). Also moved `canvas.hidden` toggling to `canvasArea.hidden` throughout (`showLoadingScreen`, `launchLevel`, `showFileTreePlaceholder`, `startReplay`) â€” hiding an *ancestor* of the Fullscreen API's target element ends fullscreen the same way hiding the element itself does, so this preserves the exact same "leaving the game ends fullscreen, a level transition doesn't" timing the old `canvas.hidden` comment described. `fitCanvasToArea()` is a no-op while `canvas` is actually the fullscreen element (checked via `document.fullscreenElement === canvas`), leaving `.scene-canvas:fullscreen`'s existing CSS to own that state entirely â€” turned out to be a redundant-but-harmless guard in practice, since the Fullscreen API's UA-level top-layer sizing overrides any inline style regardless, confirmed by direct testing. Verified via Playwright against the real dev server: measured the canvas's actual rendered size at 1920Ă—1080 (1292Ă—808, aspect ratio exactly 1.600 â€” previously would have capped at 960Ă—600), 1400Ă—900 (772Ă—483), and 1024Ă—700 (396Ă—248) windows, confirmed `canvasArea` genuinely flex-grows via computed-style inspection (not just eyeballing), and confirmed fullscreen enter (fills the full viewport) and exit (cleanly reverts to the fitted size) both still work correctly [Task 59].
- [x] ghidra causes WAY to less dmg - i had to use 2 rockets on some enemies, thats ridicolous considering its a rocket launcher â€” root cause was purely numeric: a regular (non-pack, non-Elite) enemy's HP scales with its function's complexity (`HP_PER_COMPLEXITY = 25` per point, up to `ELITE_COMPLEXITY_THRESHOLD = 40` before it splits into a pack or becomes an Elite instead), so even a single, unremarkable function with complexity 3-9 already sits at 75-225 HP â€” routinely above ghidra's old 70 ground-zero `damagePerPellet`, and a direct/near hit rarely even reaches that max once `rocketDamageAt`'s distance falloff is applied. Bumped `damagePerPellet` 70 â†’ 100 (`weapons.ts`), still felt weak in a second playtest pass â€” bumped again to 150. Blast radius/falloff floor/ammo cost/cooldown all left untouched both times, so this is purely "hits harder," not "hits farther or cheaper" (note: this does mean point-blank self-splash is now more dangerous too, an intentional side effect of the existing "standing too close to your own blast still hurts you" risk/reward design, not a new bug). Verified with `tsc --noEmit`; no other file hardcoded the old damage numbers [Task 60].
