- [x] hash in highscores should be about the workspace, not the current file - this prevents proper comparing â€” root cause: `HighscoreEntry.hash` (`recordRunHighscore` in `main.ts`) was `hashRun(JSON.stringify(parsed), campaignName())` where `parsed` is only the single file the run happened to end on (died on, or last cleared) â€” so two runs over the exact same, unedited workspace that merely ended on different levels got unrelated hashes and looked like "different code" in the Highscore UI, defeating the hash's whole purpose. Fixed by folding the hash into the existing whole-codebase background aggregation (`computeCodebaseStats`, already walking every parsable file via `flattenParsableFiles` to sum lines/complexity): each file's path-prefixed parsed-AST JSON is collected in the same stable depth-first order and NUL-joined, then hashed once via `hashRun` alongside the campaign name â€” `CodebaseStats` gained a `hash` field, and `recordRunHighscore` now prefers `codebaseStats.hash`, only falling back to the old single-file hash if the background aggregation (or `kickOffCodebaseStats`'s own catch path, which now also produces a hash) genuinely didn't finish within `recordRunHighscore`'s bounded wait. The per-level `astHash` used for replay-integrity verification (`replay.ts`'s `ReplayLevelSegment`) is a deliberately separate, still file-scoped mechanism and was left untouched. Updated `doc/user/privacy.md` and `doc/user/hud-and-ui.md` to describe the hash as workspace-wide rather than per-level. Verified with `tsc --noEmit` [Task 64].
- [x] broaden secret rooms causes for looting â€” dead code (unreachable statements after a `return`) was the only AST pattern that ever triggered a secret room, too rare a find in clean, well-tested codebases. `ParsedFile.deadCodeRegions` generalized into `ParsedFile.secretTriggers: SecretTrigger[]` (a `kind` tag plus start/end line), fed by four new detectors in `astUtils.ts` alongside the existing dead-code one: `findEmptyCatchBlocks` (a catch/except/rescue whose body is empty or contains only comments â€” a swallowed exception), `findDeprecationMarkers` (`@deprecated`, `[Obsolete]`, or a bare "deprecated" found in a comment, decorator/annotation/attribute node, or string literal â€” the last one deliberately included so Python-style triple-quoted docstrings are caught too, at the minor cost of a stray runtime string mentioning "deprecated" also counting), `findCommentedOutCodeBlocks` (contiguous comment-node runs, merged across adjacent lines since stacked `//` lines are separate sibling nodes, that span more than 6 lines or contain `{`/`}`/`;`), and `findMagicNumberBlobs` (string literals over 100 chars with no whitespace â€” Base64/hash-shaped â€” or a well-known hex magic number: `0xDEADBEEF`, `0xCAFEBABE`, `0x1337`, `0xC0FFEE`, `0xBAADF00D`, `0xDEADC0DE`, `0x8BADF00D`, `0xFEEDFACE`). Node-type vocabulary for catch/annotation/string/number literals added to the shared generic-adapter table (`vocabulary.ts`, covering all 13 generic languages) and as small local constants in the PHP/C bespoke adapters, matching each's existing per-adapter node-type-list pattern; C skips empty-catch detection entirely (the grammar has no exceptions) and scans only comments for deprecation markers (no decorator/attribute concept in scope). `placeSecretRooms` (`mapGenerator.ts`) now shuffles the combined trigger list before applying its existing 5-per-level cap, so the five pattern kinds sample fairly instead of whichever kind happens to be concatenated first (dead code) silently hogging every slot in a file that has several. Also addressed a same-thread follow-up ask: the level-start briefing now shows a "Secrets" stat (`GameMap.secretRoomCount`, threaded through `LevelStartInfo`) alongside Rooms/Enemies, so the player knows up front whether it's worth watching the walls. `doc/user/mechanics.md`, `doc/dev/game-design.md`, and the `index.html` intro screen's "How it works" mapping updated to describe the broadened trigger set; `consoleSidebar.ts` gained a matching flavor hint. Verified with `tsc --noEmit` [Task 65]. Follow-up: playtesting surfaced three real bugs from the broadened trigger set, all fixed. (1) A secret wall next to a lore terminal always triggered the terminal instead â€” the interact handler (`engine.ts`) checked lore-terminal proximity first (any terminal within `LORE_INTERACT_RADIUS = 1.8` tiles, any direction) and unconditionally returned before ever reaching `tryOpenSecretWall()`'s much tighter facing-based `SECRET_WALL_REACH = 0.9` check; flipped the order so the more deliberate facing-based secret-wall check runs first, falling back to the lore terminal only when it doesn't hit one â€” `tryOpenSecretWall()` now returns whether it actually opened something. (2) A single file produced 5 secret rooms all carved off the same anchor room â€” `placeSecretRooms` had no memory of which anchor rooms it had already used, so nothing stopped several different trigger kinds resolving to the same room (or even the same trigger's anchor) from each independently succeeding on a different side of that one room; added a `usedAnchors` set capping it at one secret room per room, walking the full shuffled trigger list (not just the first 5) until the level-wide cap is filled or triggers run out. Fixing that surfaced a deeper, pre-existing root cause shared with lore terminals and goto teleporters: `roomForLine` returned the *first* room whose entity line-range contained a trigger's line, but a method's range always sits inside its enclosing class's range too â€” since classes always sort before their own methods by `startLine`, every trigger physically inside *any* method of a class was silently anchoring to the whole class's room instead of that method's own room. Fixed `roomForLine` to pick the containing room with the smallest line span (the innermost/most specific entity) instead of the first match â€” benefits lore terminal and teleporter placement the same way, not just secret rooms. (3) Every secret room seen so far only ever contained health, never rockets â€” confirmed with the user this was simply because the rocket launcher (ghidra) wasn't unlocked yet on that run, which makes it always health by design (`hasRocketLauncher && rng() < 0.5 ? "rockets" : "health"`, the same ownership gate every other rocket-ammo source in the game already uses) â€” not a bug, no code change. All three verified against the real running `RaycasterEngine`/`MapGenerator`/parser code in headless Chromium (a stubbed `InputSource` driving real `advance(dt)` calls to confirm interact-priority; synthetic multi-pattern-in-one-function and multi-method-in-one-class PHP sources through the real parser+generator to confirm one-room-max and correct per-method anchoring) and against the real app via Playwright (GitHub-loaded `mcdope/codeenstein3d`, Secrets count rose from 3 to 5 once methods stopped collapsing into their class's room). Second follow-up: (3) turned out to actually need a fix after all â€” the underlying two-way `hasRocketLauncher ? coinflip(rockets, health) : health` table meant any player who hadn't unlocked ghidra yet really would see *only* health, run after run, with no other outcome ever possible; per explicit ask, secret-room loot needed a real chance at a weapon unlock and an armor drop too, since "if they only spawn health all the time there is no point in searching them." Reworked `placeSecretRooms`'s loot roll into a uniform pick among whatever's actually available that run: health and armor (`"swap"`, `SECRET_LOOT_SWAP_AMOUNT = 40`) are always candidates, rockets joins once the launcher's owned, and a still-unowned gdb/ghidra joins as a `"weapon"` candidate once at least one exists â€” so armor alone already breaks the "always health" complaint regardless of weapon/rocket state, and finding a secret room can now hand you a weapon outright instead of just ammo/health. `AmmoPickup` (`map/types.ts`) gained a `"weapon"` kind and an optional `weaponIndex` field (mirroring `LootDrop`'s existing shape); `RaycasterEngine.collectLoot()`'s static-pickup path gained a `"weapon"` case, and the already-owned-weapon-tops-up-ammo-instead-of-wasting-the-drop logic (previously only in `applyLoot`, for enemy-kill drops) was factored out into a new shared `grantOrTopUpWeapon()` used by both paths, so a secret-room weapon drop that turns out to already be owned (e.g. a second secret room rolling the same still-missing weapon, or the player unlocking it mid-level via an Elite kill first) gracefully falls back to an elite-sized ammo top-up instead of doing nothing. `UNLOCKABLE_WEAPONS` moved from a private `engine.ts` constant to `weapons.ts` (exported) so `main.ts` can compute a `missingWeaponIndices` list from `ownedWeapons` and hand it down through `MapGenerator.generate()` to `placeSecretRooms` as an opaque `number[]` â€” the map layer never imports engine-layer weapon concepts (a hard architecture rule, see `doc/dev/architecture.md`), same reasoning `hasRocketLauncher` already followed. Both `main.ts` call sites (live level launch and replay playback) updated identically, threading it from the correct source (`carryover`/`segment.carryover`) for each so replay determinism isn't disturbed â€” same care `hasRocketLauncher` already required. Loot-billboard rendering needed no changes at all: `collectLootBillboards` was already structurally typed against `LootDrop["kind"]` rather than `LootDrop` itself, so a secret room's `"weapon"` pickup automatically gets the same pulsing vio