le opened, converting it all to floor at once, instead of only the single tile the player interacted with â€” opening the door reveals the whole room in one beat, as it visually always appeared to. Also hardened the room-placement "clear" check with a 1-tile margin around the footprint (not just the footprint itself) before carving, so two different secret rooms can never end up 4-connected/touching â€” without it, the new flood-fill-on-open could otherwise leak from one room into a second, unrelated one if their footprints ever happened to abut. Confirmed harmless to existing pathfinding/collision/scoring: `SECRET_WALL_TILE` was already treated as solid/impassable everywhere (player collision, enemy AI, `shortestPath`'s BFS) identically to plain wall, and the sole *walkable-tile* consequence is that the "100% Clear" score bonus's denominator now actually excludes secret-room interiors as `isWalkableTile`'s own doc comment already (inaccurately, until now) claimed â€” previously only the single door tile was excluded, with the interior silently counted despite being unreachable before opening. Verified against the real parser+`MapGenerator`+`RaycasterEngine` in headless Chromium: flood-filled every `SECRET_WALL_TILE` component on a real generated map and confirmed the component count matches `secretRoomCount` with no undersized (1-tile) or merged components; rendered the real minimap and confirmed every tile of every secret room's footprint (not just the door) pixel-matches plain wall exactly; and drove a real engine interact through a real secret door, confirming the *entire* connected 10-tile room flips to floor in one action, not just the tile faced.
