- [x] ensure engine is paused when canvas is not focussed â€” the existing pause-on-blur only fired on the whole *window* losing focus (alt-tab). It never checked whether the canvas itself was the focused element, so `InputController`'s keydown/keyup listeners (bound to `window`) still fired while, say, the GitHub-repo sidebar text field had focus: typing there sent WASD/Space/Tab/etc. straight into the game (moving the player, firing, toggling the automap) and even blocked the letters themselves from being typed, since `preventDefault()` ran unconditionally for movement keys/Space/Tab. Moved the gameplay keydown/keyup listeners from `window` to the canvas element itself (`input.ts`), so they now only ever fire while the canvas is the actually-focused DOM element; added a `blur` listener on the canvas (alongside the existing `window` one) that forces the same pause-and-clear-keys path as an alt-tab, so losing focus to any other on-page control now pauses the game exactly like it already did for losing focus to another app. `onCanvasClick` now also explicitly calls `canvas.focus()` for browsers (Safari) that don't auto-focus a clicked non-text element. Verified against the real dev server via Playwright: with the canvas focused, W visibly advances the minimap marker; clicking into the GitHub repo text field pauses the game (the existing "PAUSED / Click to resume, or press Esc again" overlay appears) and typing "wasd test" (including the space) lands correctly in the field instead of moving/firing/toggling the automap; merely refocusing the canvas (without a real click) correctly leaves it paused, matching the pre-existing click/Escape-to-resume design rather than silently un-pausing on focus alone. Follow-up: the canvas-blur-forces-pause half of this fix introduced a real regression â€” pressing Escape while playing (pointer-locked) stopped pausing the game at all. Root cause: real browsers (headless Chromium doesn't reproduce this, which is why the earlier verification missed it) also release pointer lock as a mandatory side effect of Escape while locked, and that release blurs the canvas a moment later, either just before or just after the Escape keydown itself is processed depending on timing; `RaycasterEngine.advance()` drains blur and Escape in the same frame (`if (consumeBlur()) isPaused = true; if (consumeEscape()) isPaused = !isPaused;`), so the blur-forced pause and Escape's own toggle collided and canceled each other out regardless of which order they landed in. A first attempt at fixing this with a timing-window guard in `input.ts` (suppress the canvas-blur pause if it followed an Escape press within ~100ms) only covered the escape-then-blur ordering and still broke on the reverse â€” a real browser can blur the canvas *before* the Escape keydown is even dispatched to the page at all, meaning a canvas-scoped keydown listener could miss the event entirely. Replaced both attempts with two changes: (1) Escape's own keydown handling moved out of the canvas-scoped listener into a dedicated `window`-level one (`onWindowEscape`, `input.ts`) â€” the same reasoning `GameHud`'s own overlay-dismiss listener already uses window-scoping for â€” so it's guaranteed to fire regardless of where DOM focus actually lands; (2) `RaycasterEngine.advance()` now resolves Escape as authoritative over a same-frame blur instead of two independent writes (`if (escaped) isPaused = !isPaused; else if (blurred) isPaused = true;`), so Escape always wins regardless of which order the two fired in within that frame, and the input-layer timing-guess machinery could be deleted entirely. Verified in headless Chromium by manually dispatching both race orderings (Escape-then-blur and blur-then-Escape) directly on `window`/the canvas â€” both now resolve to a correct pause from a genuinely-running state â€” and reconfirmed plain Escape toggling, sidebar-click-forces-pause, and typing into the sidebar text field all still work exactly as before. Second follow-up: still didn't actually fix it â€” the user confirmed live that Escape while playing only released the mouse lock and never paused. The real root cause was more fundamental than a race: real browsers deliberately do NOT dispatch a `keydown` event at all for the specific Escape press that exits pointer lock â€” a documented Pointer Lock API security measure (so a page can never detect or interfere with the user's own escape hatch) â€” meaning `onWindowEscape` never sees that keypress no matter where it's bound. Headless Chromium never surfaced this because it doesn't implement real pointer-lock release on Escape either (confirmed: `document.pointerLockElement` stayed the canvas after a synthesized Escape press throughout every earlier "verification," which is why all of that testing was blind to the actual bug). Fixed by detecting the *loss of pointer lock itself* instead of trying to catch the keypress that causes it: added a `pointerlockchange` listener (`onPointerLockChange`, `input.ts`) that queues a new edge-triggered `pointerUnlockQueued` signal whenever `document.pointerLockElement` stops being the canvas â€” this is the only reliable channel left, and it doesn't care what caused the unlock (Escape being the common case, but it's correct for any cause). Threaded a matching `consumePointerUnlock()` through `InputSource`/`InputController`/`ReplayPlaybackInput` and a `pointerUnlock` field through `InputSnapshot` (`input.ts`, `replay.ts`) so replay recording/playback stays byte-faithful. `RaycasterEngine.advance()` now forces a pause on `blurred || pointerUnlocked`, with Escape's own toggle still taking priority if a real keydown *also* lands in the same frame (kept from the previous fix, since some browsers/situations may not suppress it). Verified in headless Chromium by forcing the exact real-browser signal directly â€” overriding `document.pointerLockElement` to `null` and dispatching a bare `pointerlockchange` event with *no* accompanying keydown at all â€” and confirmed the pause now fires correctly from that alone; also reconfirmed plain Escape (pointer not locked), sidebar-click-forces-pause + text field typing, resuming via click, and a keydown+pointerlockchange landing together (still resolves to Escape-wins) all still behave correctly [Task 69]
- [x] keys part of a ongoing cheat input sequence shouldnt be interpreted as input. if input started with "I", ignore following keys for controls if they could be part of a cheat. else interupt the cheat detection sequence and treat it as normal input â€” `InputController.onKeyDown` (`src/engine/input.ts`) now checks the cheat-prefix match *before* any control branch: a letter that keeps `cheatBuffer` a valid prefix of `IDDQD`/`IDKFA`/`IDCLIP` is swallowed entirely (never added to the held-keys set, never triggers R/F/etc.) and returns early, so typing e.g. "IDDQD" can no longer also strafe (D) or turn (Q) the player via those overlapping letters. The instant a typed letter stops extending every prefix, the buffer resets to empty and that letter (and anything typed after it) falls through to normal control handling again, exactly as before. Replaced the old design (a non-blocking rolling suffix-match buffer that let every cheat letter double as a live control) â€” `CHEAT_BUFFER_MAX`/slicing removed since the buffer is now naturally capped by the longest code's length. Verified in headless Chromium (bundled `input.ts` standalone via esbuild, dispatched real `KeyboardEvent`s at a canvas): typing "IDDQD" now leaves `KeyD`/`KeyQ` unheld while still firing the cheat; an interrupted sequence ("I" then "W", not a valid continuation) correctly drops the buffer and lets "W" register as normal held movement; a fresh valid sequence typed right after an interruption still fires correctly; and plain WASD with no relation to any cheat is completely unaffected [Task 70]
- [x] still annoyingly long corridors at times. if we cant solve it with geometry, add random rooms and enemies (called "edge case", visually different from other enemies and smaller) there to break the "endless walk feeling". best would be: shorter coridors AND that breakup mechanism â€” did both halves, per the note. Geometry half: `mapGenerator.ts` gained `MAX_CORRIDOR_STRAIGHT_LENGTH = 9`; a new post-carve pass (`breakUpLongCorridors`, run right after `connectRooms`) scans the fully-carved grid for straight runs past that length â€” necessary because run length is a property of the whole grid, not any single carved leg, since two unrelated corridor legs can land collinear and combine into one long run neither leg alone exceeds. Each run is interrupted by injecting a small 3x3/4x4 walkable "breakup room" into the path (`tryInjectBreakupRoom`), falling back to forcing a 90Â° jog (sever a short choke-point stretch back to wall, reroute 2-3 tiles around it) when a room would collide with existing geometry (`tryForceJog`) â€” a primary pass splits each run into evenly-spaced segments in one shot (cheap, well-distributed), with a small bounded set of wide-search safety-net rescans mopping up anything left over (two legs landing collinear, or a couple of adjacent evenly-spaced targets both landing in the same locally-blocked spot). Breakup rooms are tracked as a new `GameMap.breakupRooms: Rect[]`, deliberately kept separate from the AST-derived `Room[]` array (no synthetic `CodeEntity` needed) so every existing kind-gated system (enemy spawning, hazards, doors, secret rooms, pillars, ...) is structurally blind to them with zero changes â€” only `placeKeys`/`placeTraps`, which scan the whole grid rather than iterating `rooms`, needed an explicit exclusion. Gameplay half: every breakup room gets 1-3 new "Edge Case" enemies (`spawnEdgeCaseEnemies`, modeled on the existing TODO/FIXME "Bug" encounter's synthetic-`CodeEntity` pattern) â€” small (0.55x sprite scale), jarring 