- [x] limit engine to 60fps, no point in running faster â€” tried and abandoned; net no code change. Added a `TARGET_FPS`/`MIN_FRAME_INTERVAL_MS` throttle to the internal rAF loop (`RaycasterEngine`'s private `frame()` in `engine.ts`): every rAF tick still fired (staying vsync-aligned), but the sim/render step was skipped until a full target frame interval had elapsed since the last processed frame, with a modulo correction on `lastTime` so the cadence locked to the target instead of drifting. Verified in a headless-Chromium harness that this correctly throttled a simulated 240Hz input down toward the target while leaving a slower 30Hz input untouched. In real use on the user's own 60Hz display, though, a plain `TARGET_FPS = 60` (16.67ms threshold) didn't reliably hit a full 60fps (ordinary timer jitter dropped some legitimate ticks); raising it to 75 (13.3ms threshold) to give that jitter headroom made real performance measurably *worse* instead of better â€” lower fps, higher frame time. Since a looser threshold can only ever pass through the *same or more* real ticks, that result means the throttle itself was the problem, not a tuning target: on this hardware/engine the raw per-frame sim+render cost is already at the edge of what the pipeline can sustain, and merely checking/gating every rAF tick against a threshold (plus the resulting request/skip/re-request churn) added enough overhead to push it into contention (missed/queued paints), capping the user at ~50fps when the engine ran a clean, comfortable 60fps completely uncapped before this was ever added. Fully reverted (`frame()` back to unconditionally running `advance()` off the raw rAF delta, `TARGET_FPS`/`MIN_FRAME_INTERVAL_MS` removed) â€” confirmed via `git diff` that `engine.ts` matches its pre-Task-79 state exactly. Conclusion: this engine's real bottleneck is per-frame cost, not "running faster than useful"; a throttle here trades away headroom the renderer needs rather than saving unnecessary work. Revisit only alongside real render/sim optimization (see the open "code optimization/reuse, complexity reduction" item), not as a standalone cap [Task 79].
- [x] ship default highscores for demo campaign, record them via automated playthrough. do 10 playthroughs, keep the best 3 as default highscores with replay for players not having localStorage content yet â€” added a headless-Chromium bot (`scripts/generate-default-highscore.mjs`, `npm run generate:default-highscore`) that plays the real bundled `demo-campaign/` with genuine (non-cheated) input and bakes its best runs into `src/engine/defaultHighscore.ts`, a `DEFAULT_HIGHSCORE_ENTRIES: HighscoreEntry[]` shown only when a player's own board is empty. Navigation (`scripts/lib/routePlanner.mjs`) is a worklist over `pathfind.mjs`'s existing BFS: try a route to the exit, detour to a reachable key then a reachable locked door if blocked (mirroring `openDoorAhead()`'s "any key opens any door" rule and `mapGenerator.ts`'s solvability guarantee), and prefer routes avoiding hazard/spike tiles but fall back to crossing them (they're timed/tick damage, not instant death, and some levels â€” confirmed empirically, e.g. `main.c` â€” only have a route across one). Combat is a small heuristic: extended `window.__codeensteinTestHooks` with a new read-only `getEnemies()` (`engine.ts`, same inert-unless-`?testHooks=1` pattern as the existing two), and the bot turns toward the nearest alive+aggroed+nearby enemy and fires once roughly aimed, otherwise turns/walks toward its planned waypoint. Firing turned out to only need `Space` â€” both a single-shot weapon's edge-triggered `fireQueued` and an auto weapon's held `isFireHeld()` key off it (`this.keys.has("Space")`), so the bot never touches the mouse or Pointer Lock at all. That absence of mouse input wasn't an obvious first design: an earlier version drove firing through real `page.mouse.down()`/`up()` (reasoning "firing requires Pointer Lock"), which empirically turned out to synthesize real `mousemove` events even with no explicit move call â€” once Pointer Lock engaged, those landed as huge, uncapped mouse-look rotations (unlike k