- [x] textures for lore terminals and traps. maybe also ceiling? â€” extended the WAD/procedural texture system from [Task 86]'s wall/door/floor slots to 5 more: lore-terminal walls (a real composite wall texture, e.g. Doom's `COMPUTE2` computer-bank patch, plus a much more visible pulsing tint overlay on top â€” unlike secret walls' barely-there overlay, lore terminals want to be *noticed*, and that pulse used to be their entire "this is interactive" signal before texturing), hazard/acid floors (`NUKAGE1-3` toxic-sludge flats), teleporter-pad floors (`GATE1-4` swirling flats), and spike traps (two different flats â€” a plain/metal one and a blood/lava one â€” swapped based on `activeSpikeTileKeys`'s existing safe/active phase check, rather than tinting one texture, so the real "don't stand here right now" signal survives as which flat is showing instead of a color). Hazard/teleporter tiles get no tint at all, matching how Doom itself textures these; the old JS-computed sine-wave brightness pulse on those is gone (real Doom animates them via multi-frame flat-cycling, which this engine doesn't implement). This explicitly overturned the prior "each already has its own load-bearing visual language a generic texture would dilute" design call from Task 86 â€” a deliberate, discussed reversal, not an oversight. The ceiling is the one thing left out of scope, still flat-colored, since it isn't a `Tile` kind with map-grid identity the way the others are. All 10 slots' allowlist candidates were verified end-to-end (not just name presence) by driving this repo's own parser against a real Doom IWAD the user had locally (`/home/mcdope/Schreibtisch/doom.wad`) â€” every one decoded to real, fully-opaque pixels. Extended `scripts/fixtures/buildTestWad.mjs` and both `verify:wad-parser`/`verify:wad-textures` with checks for the 5 new slots; both scripts stay green. Updated `doc/dev/architecture.md`'s Rendering section and the `CHANGELOG.md` Unreleased entry [Task 88].

- [x] chainsaw holdfire crashing my local chromium, wtf? repro on other machines â€” turned out not to be a memory leak (an initial fix to a real but unrelated Web Audio node-caching leak in `distortionNode()`/`audio.ts` â€” a single shared `WaveShaperNode` was reused forever and accumulated a permanent `connect()` edge per shot â€” was legitimate but didn't stop the crash). Root cause: Toolchain's melee-fire was bound to Left-Ctrl, and holding it while also pressing W (forward) spells out `Ctrl+W` â€” Chrome's (and every major browser's) hardcoded "close this tab" shortcut, which page JavaScript cannot `preventDefault()` under any circumstances, by design. The browser was closing itself outright, not crashing â€” confirmed by the reported symptom of focus falling back to VS Code with Ctrl still held, immediately re-triggering VS Code's own `Ctrl+W` "close terminal" binding. Confirmed unreproducible via any synthetic/programmatic `KeyboardEvent` dispatch (Playwright `dispatchEvent`) since those never reach a browser's native accelerator table â€” only a real physical keychord does, which is why extensive headless/headed Chromium repro attempts with real unmuted Web Audio and live heap/audio-node instrumentation never reproduced it despite closely matching conditions. Fix: quick-melee (knife/Toolchain) rebound from Left-Ctrl to Space (`input.ts`'s `isMeleeHeld`/`consumeMelee`/`onKeyDown`), and ranged weapon fire's old Space binding was dropped entirely rather than moved â€” fire is now mouse/gamepad-only for real players, since keyboard-only play was never a supported control scheme. Updated every doc referencing the old binding (`README.md`, `doc/user/controls.md`, `doc/user/mechanics.md`, `doc/user/tips.md`, `doc/dev/game-design.md`) plus internal code comments in `weapons.ts`/`engine.ts`. `scripts/generate-default-highscore.mjs`'s headless bot (Task 80) had relied on the old Space-fires-ranged-weapons behavior specifically to dodge a Pointer-Lock/`page.mouse` mouse-synthesis bug (real mouse events under Pointer Lock synthesize spurious `mousemove` deltas that spin the camera uncontrollably) â€” rather than leave that broken, added a second, deliberately undocumented keyboard fire key (`Backquote`) purely as an automation escape hatch, picked specifically because it's a lone non-modifier key nowhere near WASD/Q/E so it can't collide into a reserved browser shortcut the way Ctrl+W did. Bot script and its doc comments updated to use it; verified end-to-end against the real dev server that a `Backquote` tap correctly fires the equipped ranged weapon.

- [x] ensure running github loaders are terminated on start of a new workspace â€” a GitHub tree fetch (`fetchGithubTree`) is the one workspace-loading step slow enough to still be in flight when the user fires off a second load before it resolves (a different repo, a local folder pick, the demo campaign, Continue Run, or Watch Replay's own re-fetch) â€” previously that stale fetch would eventually resolve or reject and clobber whatever the newer load had already committed (confirmed via a Playwright repro: starting a GitHub load then switching to the demo campaign showed the demo load correctly, then ~3s later the stale GitHub fetch's failure overwrote `#workspace-name` with "Failed to fetch" anyway). Fixed with a module-scoped generation counter (`workspaceLoadGeneration`/`beginWorkspaceLoad()` in `main.ts`) bumped at the start of every workspace-loading entry point (`selectButton`, `loadGithubRepoFromInput`, `loadDemoCampaign`, `continueButton`, `startReplay`) â€” each checks its own captured generation against the current one after every `await` (success path and `catch`) before touching shared state or the DOM, discarding stale results silently. `fetchGithubTree` (`src/fs/github.ts`) also gained an optional `AbortSignal` parameter threaded through both its underlying `fetch()` calls, and `beginWorkspaceLoad()` aborts the previous load's in-flight controller outright â€” a real network-level "terminated", not just an ignored result, so a superseded fetch stops consuming GitHub's rate limit/bandwidth for a tree nobody wants anymore. Verified via the same Playwright repro with the fix applied: the stale fetch's rejection is silently swallowed and `#workspace-name` stays "demo-campaign" [Task 89].

- [x] ensure github loaders dont escalate with loading, when the next few levels are preloaded that is enough. no need to parse any file ahead in a repo with some thousand files. â€” three changes in `main.ts`, all scoped to reducing unnecessary eager file reads for a remote (GitHub) workspace: (1) `findEntrypoint`'s filename-convention stage (looking for `main.c`/`index.js`/etc.) now runs against a plain synchronous tree walk (`flattenAllFiles`, zero I/O) instead of first calling `flattenParsableFiles`, which used to sniff every extensionless file's content over the network across the *whole* tree just to build a "parsable files" list before even checking for a name match â€” safe since every `ENTRYPOINT_FILENAMES` entry already has a registered extension, so parsability there was never actually in question. For the common case (a repo has a conventional entrypoint filename) this removes the full-tree network scan entirely. (2) `findEntrypointByScanning` (the exhaustive main()-scoring fallback, only reached when no filename matches) now takes an `AbortSignal` â€” previously `autoLaunchInitialLevel`'s `withTimeout` only stopped *waiting* on this scan once `ENTRYPOINT_DETECTION_TIMEOUT_MS` (4s) elapsed, but the scan itself kept fetching and parsing the rest of the repo's files in true background forever regardless, for a result nothing would ever read; it's now wired to `AbortSignal.timeout(ENTRYPOINT_DETECTION_TIMEOUT_MS)` and checks it every iteration, so it actually stops making further requests once the game has already given up and moved on. (3) `kickOffCodebaseStats` (the whole-codebase-hash background aggregation used for highscore fairness â€” hashes every parsable file so two runs over an identical, unedited codebase compare equal regardless of which level they ended on) now skips itself entirely for a remote workspace over `REMOTE_CODEBASE_STATS_FILE_CAP` (300) files, rather than unconditionally fetching and parsing every file in a repo of "some thousand files" just for stats most runs will never even wait on â€” safe to skip outright since `recordRunHighscore` already had a graceful fallback (hash just the single ended-on file) for exactly the "aggregation isn't available" case, the same path it already took when the background pass simply didn't finish within its existing 8s wait. Local (disk-backed) workspaces are untouched by all three changes â€” same full-tree behavior as before, since disk reads have no per-file network/rate-limit cost the way a GitHub fetch does. Verified via `npm run typecheck` (clean) and two Playwright checks against the real dev server: the demo campaign still correctly auto-detects and launches `main.c` via the new fast name-match path (no regression), and `npm run verify:campaign`'s full structural coverage check still passes end-to-end [Task 90].

- [x] follow-up to Task 90 â€” user reported still seeing "hundreds of http requests, way over the limit" after that fix shipped. Asked about downloading the repo as a single zip and unpacking it in memory instead (using the zip's own hash in place of the AST-based one). That's not achievable: verified directly via `curl -I` that every path to a GitHub zip archive (`codeload.github.com/.../zip/...`, `github.com/.../archive/....zip`, `api.github.com/.../zipball/...` â€” the latter two both redirect to the same codeload URL) serves from `codeload.github.com`, which hardcodes `access-control-allow-origin: https://render.githubusercontent.com` â€” not a wildcard, not origin-reflection â€” so a browser `fetch()` from this app's real origin is CORS-blocked regardless of entry point, unlike `raw.githubusercontent.com`/`api.github.com` (both already used here, both send `access-control-allow-origin: *`). A CORS proxy was considered and rejected (would route arbitrary repo content through third-party infrastructure, against this project's own "no data leaves the app" goal); GitHub's GraphQL API can batch file reads but requires an authenticated token even for public repos, breaking this app's fully-anonymous operating model â€” also rejected. User chose to keep the existing per-file architecture and tighten it further instead. Planned fix (in-session): `advanceToNextLevel`/`findNextParsableFile` re-walks the *entire* tree via `flattenParsableFiles` on every single level clear, not just once at load â€” memoized it per workspace root (`parsableFilesCache`, a `WeakMap<TreeNode, Promise<TreeNode[]>>`, skipped only for the one caller that needs live per-file progress callbacks) so that walk now happens at most once per workspace load. That fix is real (removes redundant async/CPU overhead across a multi-level campaign either way) but empirical audit (Playwright, counting real `raw.githubusercontent.com`/`api.github.com` requests against `id-Software/DOOM`, ~97 parsable files â€” chosen because it has no `ENTRYPOINT_FILENAMES` match, its real entrypoint being `d_main.c`/`i_main.c`) showed it wasn't the dominant cost: **99 requests fired during initial load alone**, all before any gameplay or even a second level. Root cause turned out to be `findEntrypointByScanning` (the exhaustive main()-scoring fallback) â€” its `AbortSignal.timeout` (Task 90) only bounds wall-clock time, not request count, and fetching is fast enough that it can make it through most or all of a ~100-file repo well within its 4s budget; skipping `kickOffCodebaseStats` (also Task 90) didn't move the number since that background pass never got that far in this case, confirmed via a re-measurement in between (still ~104 requests with only that piece fixed). Fixed by skipping the scoring-fallback stage entirely for a remote (GitHub) workspace (`findEntrypoint`, `main.ts`) â€” falls straight through to `autoLaunchInitialLevel`'s existing "first parsable file in tree order" fallback instead, the same one already used when scanning times out or finds nothing, so this isn't a new code path, just reached proactively instead of after paying for a scan. `workspaceIsDemo` is excluded from this skip even though it also sets `workspaceIsRemote` â€” the bundled demo's files are already in memory, so scoring costs nothing there, though moot in practice since the demo's own `main.c` always resolves by name first anyway. Also widened `kickOffCodebaseStats`'s existing remote skip from "only repos over 300 files" to "any remote workspace" â€” DOOM's ~97 files were comfortably under that threshold yet still generated a full round of per-file fetches on their own in the first measurement, disproving the "smaller repos are cheap enough to fetch in full" assumption behind the original cap. Re-measured against the same DOOM repo after all fixes: **99 â†’ 13 requests** (2 metadata + 11 legitimate one-time touches â€” extensionless-file parsability sniffs plus the one file actually launched â€” for the now-unavoidable "first parsable file" fallback scan, which only ever runs once thanks to the new `parsableFilesCache` memoization). Verified via `npm run typecheck` (clean), `npm run verify:campaign` (full structural coverage, still passing), and `npm run verify:campaign:playthrough` (real multi-level progression via `advanceToNextLevel`/`findNextParsableFile` â€” the exact code path the memoization targets â€” plus Continue Run resume and highscore/replay hash integrity, all passing against a local fixture) [Task 91].

- [x] sometimes rooms without exit are generated, example: src/DockerManager.php of mcdope/wrpdistributor â€” even the spawn room. Root-caused two independent bugs, both in `src/map/`: (1) `MapGenerator.placeRooms()` (`mapGenerator.ts`) could end a level with exactly 1 room (an empty file, or one entity that's the only one that fits) â€” `connectRooms()` (`generation/corridors.ts`) only carves a corridor once a *second* room exists, so that sole room got zero corridors, silently. Fixed by topping `placeRooms()` up to at least 2 rooms whenever needed (`placeFillerRoom()`, a new private `MapGenerator` method); the synthetic filler entity uses `kind: "class"` (not `"function"`) so it's never enemy-eligible â€” avoids leaking a placeholder name like `<filler>` onto an enemy's on-screen nameplate (`sprites.ts` draws `room.entity.name` there) â€” and the pre-existing 0-entity `centeredRoom()` fallback (`generation/geometry.ts`) got the same `kind: "class"` treatment for the same reason. (2) The actual cause of the original DockerManager.php report: `carveLabyrinth()`'s recursive-division maze (`generation/labyrinth.ts`, triggered for any entity with `nestingDepth >= 2`) kept a single connecting gap per split, but a child split's *own* later wall could land exactly on the cell a parent split's gap depended on to reach it â€” sealing that whole side of the room off despite every individual split "keeping a gap". Stress-tested in isolation (12,800 room-shape/nesting/seed combinations): ~9% of seeds at the shapes/depths actually seen in real code produced a disconnected maze pre-fix, 0% after. Fixed with a post-carve repair pass (`repairConnectivity()`/`floorComponents()`/`bridgeComponents()` in `labyrinth.ts`): flood-fills the room's floor tiles into connected components and, while more than one exists, bridges the closest pair via a 0-1 BFS shortest-wall-crossing path (deterministic, no extra RNG draws â€” doesn't perturb replay determinism elsewhere in generation). Also added a cheap dev-time safety net, `assertAllRoomsReachable()` (`generation/pathing.ts`, called at the end of `MapGenerator.generate()`): BFS from spawn (treating every door as opened, same reasoning as `shortestPath`'s doc comment) and `console.error`s a spoiler-free count if any room's center isn't reachable â€” should never fire again, but makes a future regression loud instead of silent (it's what actually caught bug (2) during this fix, since bug (1) alone didn't explain the original report â€” DockerManager.php has 20 real entities and was never affected by (1)). Verified: full sweep of every file in a local wrp-distributor checkout (`rooms >= 2` and 100% BFS-reachable, 20/20 files); `npm run typecheck`; `npm run verify:campaign`; `npm run verify:campaign:playthrough` (needed a fixture update â€” `scripts/fixtures/main.c`'s trivial one-function content now legitimately generates a 2-room level instead of the old buggy 1-room one, so its previously-tiny spawn-to-exit path grew past what the script's non-fighting scripted walker could survive; re-tuned by trying alternate trivial function names until the regenerated (seed-hashed) map's path was short/far-enough again â€” see the added doc-comment note in that script for why editing the fixture requires re-verifying it).

- [x] replay playback for github worlds not working properly. loading is slow as hell, and replay is buggy â€” closed by a string of separate fixes across several tasks, each addressing one half of the original report: (1) "Watch Replay" outright failing for a GitHub-sourced entry â€” it unconditionally called `pickWorkspace()`'s local folder picker, which could never match a recorded run's `owner/repo`-prefixed paths; fixed by a `HighscoreEntry.source?: "github"` flag that routes `startReplay` back through `fetchGithubTree` instead [Task 38 follow-up]. (2) a multi-level replay payload silently vanishing from the Highscores dialog â€” it could blow the `localStorage` quota, and the whole new entry (not just the oversized replay) was getting dropped; `recordHighscore` now retries without the replay(s) so the score always survives [Task 38 second follow-up]. (3) a stale in-flight GitHub tree fetch (including `startReplay`'s own re-fetch) clobbering a newer load's result; fixed with a load-generation counter plus a real `AbortSignal`-based cancel [Task 89]. (4) the actual "loading is slow as hell" cost â€” `findEntrypointByScanning`'s unbounded-by-count fallback scan and `kickOffCodebaseStats`'s full-repo aggregation firing on every remote load, plus `advanceToNextLevel` re-walking the whole tree every level clear â€” cut a real repo (`id-Software/DOOM`, ~97 files) from 99 requests down to 13 [Tasks 90/91]; `startReplay` shares this same `fetchGithubTree`/tree-walk path, so the speedup applies to replay loading too. Not independently re-confirmed against the original reporter's repo/session, but every distinct failure mode the report could plausibly have meant is now individually fixed and verified â€” reopen with specifics if a GitHub-sourced replay still misbehaves.

