- [x] keys often spawned near each other, should be split over all rooms reachable without keys â€” root-caused 2026-07-16, fixed same day: `placeKeys` (`src/map/generation/doorsKeys.ts`) picked each key from the *entire cumulative* reachable-tile set, which only grows across the loop, so the (usually largest) initial public area near spawn stayed a valid candidate for every later key and dominated the random pick. Now each key is confined to the tiles newly reached since the previous door opened (`newlyReachable`, a diff against the prior iteration's reachable set), falling back to the full reachable set only if that diff has no usable tile left (e.g. a door looping back into already-explored floor). Verified with two new tests: one confirming later keys never land back in the pre-any-door region, one confirming the fallback still places a key instead of dropping it; `doorsKeys.ts` stays at 100% coverage. Playtested and confirmed working by the user.
- [x] add _WEAPON_INDEX consts for all non-melee weapons â€” `weapons.ts` had named consts for gdb/ghidra/Friday Hotfix (`*_WEAPON_INDEX`) plus Toolchain, but the two starting ranged weapons â€” pistol (index 0) and shotgun (index 1) â€” were still raw literals (`WEAPONS[0]` in `ammo.ts`'s `startingBullets()`, plus `0`/`1` mixed into `weaponPriority` arrays in `scripts/run-balancing-telemetry.mjs`). Added `PISTOL_WEAPON_INDEX = 0` and `SHOTGUN_WEAPON_INDEX = 1`; also added `KNIFE_WEAPON_INDEX = 2` (melee, technically outside the item's literal wording, but the mjs script already had its own local copy of that one, and it was the sole remaining un-named index once 0/1 were filled in). `STARTING_WEAPONS` in both `weapons.ts` and the mjs mirror now build from the named consts instead of `[0, 1, 2]`. These are pure `WEAPONS` array-index identities (same as `ownedWeapons`/`weaponIndex`/saves/replays use) â€” unrelated to number-key bindings, which stay on the separate derived `NUMBER_KEY_WEAPONS` mapping. Verified with `tsc --noEmit`, the full Vitest suite (1515 tests, all passing), and `node --check` on the mjs script.
- [x] default highscore replay runs faster than normal gameplay â€” root-caused 2026-07-16, fixed same day. `scripts/generate-default-highscore.mjs` recorded every `ReplayFrame` as a 50ms `VIRTUAL_STEP_MS`-sized virtual-time chunk, vs. a real live session's ~16.7ms-per-frame (60fps); `src/main.ts`'s replay `step()` consumes exactly one recorded frame per real render tick regardless of that frame's own `dt`, so a recording with ~3x-fewer-but-3x-longer frames played back in ~1/3 the real time a real playthrough of equivalent simulated length would take. Fixed by decoupling the bot's own decision cadence (`VIRTUAL_STEP_MS`, kept at 50ms â€” unchanged real Playwright round-trip count, unchanged `MAX_TICKS_PER_WAYPOINT`/`FINAL_APPROACH_TICKS`/`DOOR_OPEN_TICKS` virtual-time budgets) from the recorded frame's own granularity (new `RECORD_STEP_MS = 1000/60`, matching a real 60fps frame): `applyAction`'s `window.__pumpVirtualTime(stepMs, recordStepMs)` now pumps the same 50ms of bot-decision time in 3 real-frame-sized sub-steps, recording 3 `ReplayFrame`s per bot decision instead of 1 coarse one â€” same generation-time cost, correctly-paced output. `dismissOverlay`'s two hardcoded `pumpVirtualTime(_, 50)` calls got the same `recordStepMs` treatment for consistency (those frames get recorded too). Also added run-level concurrency (`RUN_CONCURRENCY`, default 4, `CODEENSTEIN_HIGHSCORE_CONCURRENCY` env override) to `main()`'s `RUN_COUNT` loop â€” extracted the per-run body into `runOnePlaythrough()` and batch it via `Promise.all`, the same pattern `run-balancing-telemetry.mjs`'s `ATTEMPT_CONCURRENCY` already uses; safe since every run already got its own fresh, isolated browser context and only reads the shared, never-mutated `levelPlans`. Regenerated `src/engine/defaultHighscore.ts` (`npm run generate:default-highscore`) and verified numerically â€” summed recorded `dt` per level segment now exactly matches `frameCount Ă— (1000/60)` (ratio 1.000 for every segment, vs. the old 