Follow-up (2026-07-16, user-reported, same day): two problems with that first ship. **(a) Wasted wall space** â€” `MapGenerator` allocates a full `size Ă— size` grid of solid wall (`mapGenerator.ts:109-110`) and carves rooms/corridors out of it; confirmed this is real engine data, not a rendering artifact, but the exported PNG was painting *all* of it, producing a huge tan rectangle with the actual maze occupying a small corner. Fixed entirely within `exportView.ts` (no engine/`mapGenerator.ts` changes): a wall tile only draws if at least one of its 8 neighbors is real content (floor/hazard/door/teleporter/spike/lore/opened-secret) â€” giving exactly a 1-tile wall border ring around actual rooms â€” everything else is skipped and stays transparent (the canvas's own default). The output canvas is also cropped to the tight bounding box of everything actually drawn (content + its border ring, no extra padding layered on top â€” that would have just doubled the margin), instead of sizing to the full generated grid. **(b) Button discoverability** â€” user reported it took ~2 minutes to find. Root-caused, not guessed: `#viewport` (`style.css`) is a vertically-centered flex column with `overflow: hidden` â€” clips, doesn't scroll â€” and the button was `appendChild`'d *last*, after `hint` and the fairly tall keybinding-legend grid, so it risked being exactly what got clipped, and even when visible used `.settings-btn` (width:100%, deliberately muted, built for the sidebar's vertical stack) so it barely stood out. Fixed by `viewport.insertBefore(button, hint)` (now the first thing below the canvas, right under the win overlay) plus a new dedicated `.export-map-btn` class styled like this app's other primary CTAs (`#select-workspace` et al.: accent-colored, bold, sized to content) with an đź–Ľď¸Ź icon prefix. **(c) User asked whether the wasted-wall-space problem also costs real engine performance, not just export cosmetics** â€” investigated and confirmed a real, plausible (not yet profiled) mechanism: `PathField.ensure()` (`pathField.ts:36-50`, the shared player-rooted BFS distance field every chasing enemy steers by) allocates `Int32Array(map.width*map.height)` once per level but calls `this.dist.fill(-1)` on *every reflood* (routine during normal movement, not just once per level) â€” an O(widthĂ—height) cost that scales with the entire grid including all the never-visited filler (the BFS traversal itself stays cheap regardless, since wall-gated expansion never enters solid space). `automap.ts` is unaffected (already windowed to a viewport-sized region). Logged as its own separate `notes` item below rather than fixed now â€” more invasive (touches map generation + `PathField` + any other `map.width`/`height` consumer), needs its own profiling pass first. Verified: `tsc --noEmit` clean; full Vitest suite (1530 tests) at 100% coverage, including 2 new `exportView.test.ts` cases (crops to content+border, skips deep filler even *within* the cropped box using a two-separate-rooms-with-a-gap fixture) and updated `main.test.ts` assertions for the new button text; live Playwright spot-check confirmed the button sits comfortably within the viewport (not clipped) immediately below the canvas, and the re-exported PNG is now a tightly-cropped image with a thin wall border and a transparent background instead of a mostly-solid-wall rectangle.
- [x] investigate whether PathField's full-grid reset actually costs real performance (follow-up to (c) above, 2026-07-16, same day) â€” **measured, ruled out, no fix needed.** `MapGenerator`'s grid is clamped to `[minSize, maxSize] = [64, 160]` (`mapGenerator.ts:60-61`), so the worst possible grid is 160Ă—160 = 25,600 tiles. Benchmarked the two costs that actually scale with grid size (Node `process.hrtime.bigint()`, V8 â€” the same engine Chrome uses): the recurring per-reflood `dist.fill(-1)` cost averaged **~0.0015ms per call** at the worst-case 160Ă—160 size (1000 calls totaled 1.484ms) â€” reflooding only happens on real tile-crossings (roughly a few times/sec during normal movement, not every frame), so even 100 refloods/sec would total ~0.15ms/sec against a 16.67ms *per-frame* budget at 60fps; the one-time per-level array allocation averaged **~0.06ms** at the same worst-case size (100 allocations totaled 6.03ms), paid once per level load, not per-frame. Also confirmed no other cost scales with total grid size: `PathField.distAt()` (the per-enemy lookup) is an O(1) typed-array read, the BFS flood itself only ever visits reachable tiles (wall-gated expansion never enters solid filler, so it was never proportional to filler size to begin with â€” only the `fill(-1)` reset was), and `automap.ts` is already windowed to a viewport-sized region, not the full grid. The theoretical O(widthĂ—height) scaling flagged in the note above was correct, but the constant factor (native `TypedArray.fill`/allocation, both essentially memory-bandwidth-bound memset operations) is small enough that even this game's largest possible grid never turns it into a real bottleneck â€” cropping `MapGenerator`'s grid to content bounds (the fix speculated about above) would not produce a measurable improvement, and isn't worth the real invasiveness it'd add (touches map generation, `PathField`, and every other `map.width`/`height` consumer's coordinate space) for a cost that isn't actually there. No source changes made â€” this is purely a measured verdict. Doesn't affect the level-export PNG's own crop/transparency fix above, which was a real visual problem regardless of runtime cost.
- [x] generalize telemetry bot into a reusable bot class, use it also for highscore defaults creation (and later multiplayer bots maybe). highscore creation should run all skill levels until each one has 3 runs reaching level 4 for casual, level 5 for gamer and level 6 for pro, keep the best one for each â€” shipped 2026-07-17, per plan `~/.claude/plans/generalize-telemetry-bot-into-kind-popcorn.md`. `scripts/run-balancing-telemetry.mjs`'s ~1450 lines of navigation/combat/loot decision-making extracted into a `Bot` class (`scripts/lib/bot.mjs`, config now explicit constructor opts instead of module-level `process.env` consts read once at import); `scripts/lib/qualifyLoop.mjs` extracted the generic retry-until-N-qualifying-runs pattern shared by both the telemetry harness and the highscore generator; `scripts/lib/virtualClock.mjs` deduped a previously byte-for-byte-duplicated `installVirtualClock`. `scripts/generate-default-highscore.mjs` rewritten on top of these exactly as specified: plays each of the 3 skill profiles (Casual/Gamer/Pro) until 3 runs qualify (clears level 4/5/6 respectively â€” `QUALIFY_LEVEL_INDEX_BY_PROFILE`), keeps the single best-scoring qualifying run per profile (3 entries total), replacing the old profile-blind "10 generic runs, keep top 3" approach. No `HighscoreEntry` schema change â€” the 3 entries aren't tagged with which profile produced them.
  - **Verification surfaced a real, unrelated bug**: the smarter/deeper-surviving bot made the regenerated `defaultHighscore.ts` balloon to **84MB** (3 entries Ă— 14+ levels of recorded replay frames each) â€” this is what actually crashed a prior session mid-verification (timed out `highscores.test.ts`'s 30s limit and OOM'd the full Vitest suite; parsing an 84MB array-of-objects literal into an AST is the expensive part, not decoding the data itself). Fixed by shipping the entries gzip+base64-encoded (`gz1:` prefix, reusing `storageCompression.ts`'s existing localStorage-compression scheme) instead of a plain array literal â€” 84MB â†’ 618KB (136x), verified byte-identical after decompression and working end-to-end (Highscores dialog renders, Watch Replay plays back cleanly) in a real browser. Found and fixed a second latent bug while there: `storageCompression.ts`'s `gzip`/`gunzip` used `new Blob([bytes]).stream()`, which jsdom's `Blob` shim doesn't implement (every real browser does) â€” meant the real compression path had never actually been exercised by any test (`compressForStorage`'s try/catch silently fell back to plain JSON). Replaced with a small `ReadableStream`-based helper, which works identically under jsdom and in real browsers.
  - **Verified**: full suite (1543/1543), `tsc --noEmit`, and coverage (100% on every touched file) all clean. `npm run balancing:scan` post-refactor: 353 anomalies, 0 nav-warns, max stall 63 ticks â€” within this project's established normal range, no navigation/combat regression from the extraction. `run-balancing-campaign.mjs` and `watch-bot-sessions.mjs` (both untouched consumers of the refactored exports) confirmed still working.
- [x] highscore bot presses fire key so fast, the pistol becomes a smg lmao. it should be human like, depending on skill level â€” fixed 2026-07-17, same day as the `Bot` class extraction above. Root cause, confirmed by reading the engine source: semi-auto ranged weapons (pistol/shotgun/ghidra) have no `fireIntervalSec` cooldown at all (`updateFiring` in `engine.ts` â€” "the pistol/shotgun have none, so they're... fire exactly as fast as the player can press/click") â€” `Bot#applyAction` dispatches a fresh `Backquote` keydown every single decision tick the bot decides to fire, and since `consumeFire()` is edge-triggered per keydown with no `e.repeat` involved (synthetic events never set it), a target locked on for many consecutive ticks fired once per tick: ~20/sec at the headless 50ms tick rate, ~7.7/sec even in headed real-time mode â€” both far beyond any human trigger-pull rate. Auto weapons (gdb/Friday Hotfix) were never affected â€” their own engine-side `fireIntervalSec` cooldown already paces them realistically while the key is held.
  - **Fix**: new `profile.fireCooldownMs` (Casual 220ms/~4.5 shots-per-sec, Gamer 160ms/~6.25, Pro 120ms/~8.3 â€” all plausible real semi-auto trigger-pull rates, tightestâ†’loosest matching the existing `fireAngleEps`/`rotSpeedMultiplier` skill ladder) in `run-balancing-telemetry.mjs`'s `PROFILES`. `Bot` (`bot.mjs`) tracks cumulative simulated time (`this.simTimeMs`, incremented once per `applyAction` call by that call's real `stepMs`) and the sim-time of its last semi-auto shot; the ranged-fire decision branch now gates `fire` on `simTimeMs - lastFireSimTimeMs >= profile.fireCooldownMs` for any weapon *not* in the new `AUTO_RANGED_WEAPON_INDICES` set (gdb/Friday Hotfix stay unthrottled, correctly).
  - **Verified via direct trace, not assumed**: a `CODEENSTEIN_TELEMETRY_DEBUG_NAV=1` trace (Gamer/normal) measured the tick-gap between consecutive genuine semi-auto ranged fires (filtering out melee swings, which go through a completely separate `Space`-key/`meleeCooldown` path already correctly rate-limited) â€” dominant clustering at 4-5 ticks (200-250ms), matching Gamer's 160ms cooldown rounded up to tick granularity; the one apparent 2-tick outlier turned out to be a benign weapon-switch-mid-fight tracing artifact (an unthrottled auto-weapon shot correctly exempted from the cooldown), not a real violation.
  - **A real regression found and fixed in the same pass, not shipped blind**: the first `balancing:scan` after this change came back with anomaly count 473 (vs. the established 331-390 range) and max stall 179 ticks (vs. 42-91) â€” `detectAnomalies`'s `mostlyFiring` exclusion (a stationary run is only flagged as a stall if *not* mostly-firing, since holding ground and shooting is correct combat behavior) relied on `fire: true` covering most ticks of a real firefight, which was true when the bot fired every tick but is no longer true now that most ticks are spent waiting out a human-paced cooldown instead. Fixed by adding a new `fireOnCooldown` trace field (true when the bot was aimed/ready/willing to fire but held back purely by the cooldown, not by e.g. rocket-safety) and broadening the exclusion to `fire || fireOnCooldown` â€” deliberately narrow (only this specific new waiting state is exempted, not "any threat present," which would have risked masking the class of genuine stuck-in-combat bugs found earlier this project's history). Re-scan after the detector fix: anomaly count 366, max stall 62 ticks, both back within the established normal range; 3/3 qualifying in 5 attempts for all 3 profiles, unchanged from before this whole fix.
  - No `src/` changes â€” bot-script-only (`scripts/lib/bot.mjs`, `scripts/run-balancing-telemetry.mjs`), Vitest suite unaffected.
- [x] support other browsers as good as possible (ignore the non available FS api) â€” investigated (2026-07-16, no code changed yet). **Scope note (user, 2026-07-16): desktop only, mobile is explicitly not a target** â€” this game asks for a proper screen and proper input devices (mouse/keyboard/gamepad), so this is about desktop Firefox/Safari/other-Chromium-derivatives, not phones/tablets. Drops any mobile-specific platform quirks (e.g. iOS Safari's fullscreen limitations) out of scope entirely â€” not worth tracking here.
  - **File System Access API: already fully handled, nothing to do here** â€” `src/fs/workspace.ts`'s `isFileSystemAccessSupported()` feature-detects `window.showDirectoryPicker`, and `main.ts` already disables the "Select Workspace"/"Continue Run" buttons with a clear "Use Chrome, Edge, or Brave" message when it's missing, rather than letting a click throw. Matches the note's own "ignore the non available FS api" instruction exactly â€” confirming this part is already done, not a gap.
  - **Gamepad and Web Audio already have real fallback handling**: `gameHud.ts`'s gamepad poll checks `typeof navigator.getGamepads === "function"` before calling it; `audio.ts`'s `AudioContext ?? webkitAudioContext ?? null` already covers older Safari's vendor-prefixed name. Neither needs further work.
  - **Pointer Lock and Fullscreen: unprefixed, no fallback, likely fine on desktop.** `input.ts`'s `canvas.requestPointerLock()` and `document.exitFullscreen()`/`canvas.requestFullscreen()` are called with no vendor-prefixed fallback (no `webkitRequestPointerLock`/`webkitRequestFullscreen`). Both APIs' unprefixed forms have been supported in desktop Safari for years (Pointer Lock since 12.1/2019, Fullscreen even earlier) â€” on a desktop-only scope, this reads as a low-risk non-issue rather than something needing active work, unlike a mobile scope where Fullscreen specifically would have been a real structural gap.
  - **The real structural gap: zero automated cross-browser verification exists anywhere in this project.** Every Playwright-driven script â€” `scripts/verify-campaign-playthrough.mjs`, `scripts/run-balancing-telemetry.mjs`, `scripts/watch-bot-sessions.mjs`, `scripts/generate-default-highscore.mjs`, `scripts/verify-wad-textures.mjs` â€” hardcodes `chromium.launch()`. Firefox/WebKit compatibility is currently completely unverified, and any regression there would be entirely invisible to this project's existing testing discipline (same class of blind spot as the "CI green doesn't mean tsc ran" lesson from earlier this session â€” a passing check isn't evidence for something it never actually exercised). Playwright already bundles Firefox and WebKit engines (no new dependency needed) â€” swapping `chromium.launch()` for `firefox.launch()`/`webkit.launch()` in even one existing verification script would be a cheap first real signal of what, if anything, currently breaks, before investing in fixing anything speculatively. This is the one real, actionable next step here.
  - **Firefox verification shipped 2026-07-17** (picked up as low-hanging-fruit item #2, after the bot fire-rate fix): new `scripts/lib/browserEngine.mjs` reads `CODEENSTEIN_VERIFY_BROWSER` (chromium/firefox/webkit, default chromium) instead of every script hardcoding `chromium.launch()`. `verify-campaign-playthrough.mjs` (OPFS-stubbed workspace, never touches the real picker) and `verify-wad-textures.mjs` (bundled demo campaign via `fetch` + WAD via a plain `<input type="file">`, no FS API at all) were the two candidates identified above â€” both wired up and re-run against real Firefox: every check passes, including `verify-wad-textures.mjs`'s strict "zero console/page errors across the whole run" assertion, and visual screenshots confirm correct rendering (procedural textures, a loaded synthetic WAD's textures, HUD/minimap all correct). Wired into CI as a blocking matrix (`verify-browser` job, `.github/workflows/verify.yml`, `browser: [chromium, firefox]`) â€” user's explicit call, weighing recurring CI cost against real coverage. One real Firefox-only quirk found and documented (not a bug): `page.reload()` fires `addInitScript` twice, once for a transient intermediate document (`location.href === ""`, `navigator.storage` genuinely undefined) that gets discarded before the script ever interacts with it â€” confirmed directly by instrumenting the init script, logged-not-asserted in the script with a doc comment explaining it.
  - **WebKit unblocked and shipped, same day**: user ran `sudo npx playwright install-deps` (`libwoff1` was the missing piece) â€” `webkit.launch()` now works. `verify-wad-textures.mjs` runs clean against it (all checks pass, zero errors â€” it never touches the File System Access API at all). `verify-campaign-playthrough.mjs` genuinely can't, though: confirmed directly (`typeof navigator.storage === "undefined"` on a plain page load) that Playwright's own WebKit build has no `navigator.storage`/OPFS support at all â€” a gap in that specific build, not a real Safari limitation (real desktop Safari has supported OPFS since 15.2). CI matrix is now `[chromium, firefox, webkit]`, with `verify:campaign:playthrough`'s step conditioned on `matrix.browser != 'webkit'` so it only runs where it can actually work. Confirmed WebKit is still a real, live, worth-testing target despite most other historically-WebKit browsers (old Opera, old Chrome) having forked to Blink over a decade ago â€” desktop Safari is exactly the platform this scope note's own "Firefox/Safari/other-Chromium-derivatives" framing already called out.
  - **A real user bug report arrived mid-investigation (2026-07-17, same day), root-caused and resolved (not a code bug)**: "Firefox shows empty canvas till focussed" â€” happens after both a page reload *and* a same-session restart-after-death (no reload involved), fixed by clicking into the canvas. Extensive automated repro attempts (headed Firefox + Chromium via Playwright, blur/focus instrumentation, pixel-content canvas checks, OPFS/reload-quirk investigation) found nothing â€” every automated case rendered correctly in well under a second. User provided two screen recordings; ffmpeg contact-sheet analysis (this project's established video-analysis technique) of the first showed the level-start briefing overlay appearing quickly, then the canvas going genuinely blank (sidebar/console still visible, no spinner, no "PAUSED" text) for ~4.5s before gameplay suddenly appeared â€” a real, reproducible-on-their-end symptom automation couldn't catch.
    - **Root-caused with hard data**: added temporary `[timing-probe]` console.log instrumentation (`performance.now()` timestamps at `GameHud.show()`, `dismiss()`, the level-start `onAck` callback, `engine.start()`, and the first 20 `frame()` callbacks incl. `document.visibilityState`/`hasFocus()`) â€” this project's console sidebar mirrors `console.log` verbatim, so it showed up directly in the user's next recording without needing DevTools. A third recording's console output was conclusive: `drawOverlay returned t=6660.0` â†’ `dismiss() invoked t=12406.0` â€” the entire ~5.75s gap sits *before* `dismiss()` is even invoked; every step after it (`onAck` â†’ `engine.start()` â†’ first `requestAnimationFrame` â†’ first rendered frame) completes in under 5ms, every time. The whole engine/render pipeline this session's earlier investigation focused on was never the problem.
    - **Real mechanism, confirmed via the user's own testing + their GNOME settings**: the user confirmed their *first* click/keypress does nothing but "activate the canvas" (i.e., refocus the browser window at the OS level) â€” only their second interaction actually reaches the page. `gsettings get org.gnome.desktop.wm.preferences focus-mode` = `'click'`, GNOME's own standard default, not a misconfiguration. This is a genuine desktop/browser window-focus interaction â€” `window.addEventListener("keydown", ...)` (what `GameHud.show()`'s dismiss listener uses) categorically cannot receive events while the OS window itself lacks real keyboard focus, and no web page can force real OS focus or detect "I don't have it yet" before the fact. Not fixable at the app-code level; not Codeenstein-specific either, would affect any page expecting immediate keyboard/click input right after a window-focus-changing action (alt-tab, reload via keyboard shortcut, etc.) under this exact desktop-environment behavior.
    - No code changes â€” the temporary `[timing-probe]` instrumentation (`src/engine/engine.ts`, `src/main.ts`, `src/ui/gameHud.ts`) was fully removed once root-caused, verified via `git restore` + a clean `tsc --noEmit`.
    - Documented for players too, per user request: `doc/user/getting-started.md`'s "The first level" section now explains the "briefing seems unresponsive" symptom inline (try clicking/pressing Start again) right where a player would actually hit it.
- [x] ensure all keys are placed so they can be found before needed, i have the feeling that it is not always the case â€” investigated 2026-07-17, real gap found and closed. `placeKeys` (`doorsKeys.ts`) already guarantees each key it *does* place sits reachable before its own door, but has one accepted fallback (its own doc comment: "skips placing a key... when every reachable tile is already used") that can leave a door with **no matching key placed anywhere** â€” a room-solvability gap, not just a findability one. The function meant to catch exactly this, `assertAllRoomsReachable` (`pathing.ts`, called at the very end of `MapGenerator.generate` after every other system has placed its tiles), turned out to not actually check it: its own doc comment assumed "generation guarantees every door is eventually openable" and treated every door as pre-opened regardless of key state, by design â€” an unverified assumption standing in for a real check.
  - **Empirically, real levels are fine**: swept 613 real, structurally-diverse third-party files across 11 supported languages (this repo's own `src/`, a broad `node_modules` sample, and a large multi-language sample pulled from `~/sources` â€” C, PHP, Python, Ruby, Go, Objective-C, Scala, TS/TSX, JS, Java, C header files), 105 of which generated at least one locked door. Zero had `keys.length < doors.length`; zero were unsolvable under a real key-consumption simulation (collect any reachable key, spend one to open a reachable locked door, repeat â€” the same model `RaycasterEngine.openDoorAhead`/`keysHeld` actually uses, shared-pool, any key opens any door). The theoretical gap is real but evidently rare enough to never have manifested in this data.
  - **Fixed anyway, since "evidently rare" isn't "structurally impossible"**: rewrote `assertAllRoomsReachable` to run the same real key-gated reachability simulation used in the sweep above (new `keys` parameter), instead of unconditionally treating every door as passable. Converts a previously-silent assumption into an actively-enforced, permanent dev-time safety net â€” exactly the job this function already existed for, just implemented against the wrong model. Zero generation-behavior change (purely a stricter verification pass); if a future change to `placeKeys`/`placeSecretRooms`/`placeTraps` ever does strand a room behind a keyless door on a real file, this now logs it loudly (spoiler-free, no coordinates, matching the function's existing convention) instead of silently shipping it.
  - **Verified**: existing `pathing.test.ts` coverage updated (the old "counts an opened door as passable" test unconditionally trusted a locked door â€” rewritten to require a real, correctly-reachable key, matching what `placeKeys` actually guarantees) plus 2 new tests: one reproducing `placeKeys`' exact accepted-fallback scenario and confirming it's now correctly flagged as an error, one confirming a legitimate multi-door key-in-sequence chain (open door A using a key reachable at spawn, discover key B only after door A opens, use it on door B) is still correctly accepted. Full suite (1545/1545, +2 net new tests), `tsc --noEmit`, and coverage (100% on every touched file, including `pathing.ts`) all clean. The existing `mapGenerator.test.ts` regression test ("never logs an unreachable-room warning for any bundled demo-campaign file") now exercises the *real* key-gated check on all 17 bundled levels, not the old unconditional one, and still passes clean.
- [x] selectable wads to be loaded via internet â€” shipped 2026-07-17 as a curated "Or pick an online texture pack" list in the sidebar, next to the existing local-file WAD picker. Architecture ended up different from the user's original ask in one key way (a correction mid-build): a direct browser `fetch()` of any of the drafted sources is impossible (checked directly â€” GitHub Release assets, `codeload.github.com`, and every small Doom-community host send no usable CORS headers), and the user's own follow-up call was to fetch+extract at **build time** instead (`scripts/fetch-online-wads.mjs`, run via `predev`/`prebuild` npm hooks, idempotent) into `public/wads/`, served same-origin at runtime â€” not committed to the repo (a first pass committed the ~170MB of extracted WAD bytes as static assets; corrected to gitignored + re-fetched per machine/CI run instead). Needed a hand-rolled ZIP reader (`scripts/lib/zipReader.mjs`, same dependency-minimalism reasoning as the WAD parser itself â€” see decisions.md) since Node has no built-in ZIP support.
