 - [ ] enemy textures from wad? if yes: what about hitbox? â€” investigated (2026-07-16, no code changed yet).
   - **Today: enemies are 100% procedural, zero WAD sprite loading exists.** `src/wad/loadWad.ts`'s `WadLoadResult` only ever loads wall/door/floor-style textures (`wallTexture`/`doorTexture`/`floorTexture`/etc.) â€” no sprite lump is read at all. Enemies are drawn in `src/engine/sprites.ts` as solid-color rectangular billboards (`enemyColor`/`enemyBodyColor`), sized by a single `sizeFactor` in `projectEnemy` (`ENEMY_SIZE`, scaled by `EDGE_CASE_SCALE`=0.55 or `ELITE_SCALE`).
   - **Loading real sprite art is feasible, same binary format already parsed**: Doom sprite lumps use the exact same "patch" pixel format as wall patches (`src/wad/patch.ts`'s `parsePatch` is already format-generic, not wall-specific) â€” no new binary parser needed. But the pipeline differs from walls: sprites are used as single patches per frame directly (no `compositeTexture.ts`-style multi-patch tiling/`TEXTURE1` step), and use Doom's frame+rotation lump-naming convention (e.g. `TROOA1`, `TROOA2A8` mirrored) that nothing in this codebase currently parses. This project's WAD-texture system also has a real security/curation stance worth respecting here, not shortcutting: `src/wad/textureAllowlist.ts` is a hand-curated, individually-IWAD-verified name list per slot (not "trust any name present") â€” real monster sprites (imp/zombieman/demon/etc.) would need the same treatment: a new, separately-verified allowlist, not a generic passthrough.
   - **The hitbox question is the real design fork, and it's grounded in something concrete**: today, hitbox and visual are *literally the same rectangle* by construction â€” `projectEnemy`'s one `sizeFactor`-derived projection is the exact object both `enemyBodyColor`'s fill (drawing) and `findTargetInProjections` (hit test, used by both ranged fire and melee's `meleeWouldHit`) operate on. Real Doom sprite art has irregular silhouettes with substantial transparent padding inside its bounding box â€” reusing today's full-rect hit test unchanged against real sprite pixels would make every enemy's hitbox visibly more generous than its drawn silhouette, a real fairness/feel regression, not just a cosmetic swap.
   - **Follow-up investigated (2026-07-16): what real silhouette-accurate hitboxes would actually take.** Turns out meaningfully cheaper than "pixel-alpha-accurate hit-test project" implies â€” the pieces already fit together well:
     - **The opacity data is already there for free.** A Doom patch's post format (`src/wad/patch.ts`) *is* its own alpha channel â€” each column's posts are exactly its runs of opaque pixels; any row not covered by a post in that column is transparent by definition. No separate alpha lookup or new data structure needed once a sprite's `Patch` is loaded â€” `patch.columns[x]` already answers "is this pixel opaque" directly.
     - **The engine's hit-test geometry is already a real 2D screen rect, not a raycaster-column hack.** `projectPoint` (`sprites.ts`) returns genuine `left/right/top/bottom` screen coordinates from one `size` value â€” `findTargetInProjections` checks a single `screenX` column against `cy` (the screen's fixed vertical center, since this engine has no mouselook pitch â€” `cy` is always `height/2`). That means mapping a hit-test point into the sprite's *native* pixel space is one clean linear interpolation per axis: `patchCol = floor((screenX - proj.left) / (proj.right - proj.left) * patch.width)`, `patchRow = floor((cy - proj.top) / (proj.bottom - proj.top) * patch.height)` â€” then look up `patch.columns[patchCol]` for a post covering `patchRow`. Elite/Edge-Case scaling doesn't complicate this at all: `proj`'s rect is already scaled, so the interpolation is unaffected by which scale factor produced it.
     - **The real new requirement is frame/rotation state, not the math.** Hit-testing needs the *exact same* patch (frame + rotation) that was actually drawn to the player that tick â€” today's system gets this for free by construction (draw and hit-test share the literal same rect object); a sprite-based version needs an explicit "current displayed patch" resolved once per enemy per tick and threaded to both the draw call and the hit test, or the two could silently diverge (a shot that visually missed the silhouette registering as a hit, or vice versa) â€” a real correctness requirement, not just an implementation detail.
     - **Blast radius**: `findTargetInProjections` is shared by ranged fire *and* melee's `meleeWouldHit` â€” a silhouette-accurate hit test would change melee timing/feel too unless deliberately scoped to ranged-only (an explicit decision to make, not an accident to discover later).
     - **Performance is a non-issue**: one column lookup + a short post-list scan per hit test (O(small) â€” a sprite has few posts per column) â€” negligible even for a multi-pellet shotgun blast checking several enemies at once.
   - **Revised recommendation**: given the above, real silhouette hitboxes are a legitimately achievable *second phase* once sprite loading itself exists (previous bullet) â€” not the much harder ask it first looked like. Still recommend shipping cosmetic-only sprites first (rectangular hitbox unchanged, zero risk to existing weapon-accuracy tuning) and treating silhouette-accurate hit-testing as a deliberate, separately-scoped follow-up, specifically because of the frame/rotation-sync requirement above â€” that's real new state to get right, worth its own focused pass and verification rather than bundling into the initial sprite-loading work.
   - **Real scope, if picked up**: new sprite-lump loading path in `loadWad.ts` (single-patch, no composite step), a new curated+IWAD-verified monster-name allowlist (same rigor as the existing wall-texture one), a decision on how many frames/rotations to support (Doom sprites can have up to 8 rotations plus walk/attack/death sequences â€” even a reduced subset is real per-enemy-kind work, not a one-line flip), and â€” if/when the silhouette-hitbox follow-up is picked up too â€” the frame-sync mechanism described above plus an explicit ranged-vs-melee scoping decision.
 - [ ] reloading for pistol, shotgun, smg and rocketlauncher, including animation and sfx. add R as hotkey to trigger early reload, else reload auto when mag/stack is emptied. mag for pistol: 9, smg: 45, shotgun: 2, rocketlauncher: 1. â€” investigated (2026-07-16, no code changed yet); bigger than the other items in this section, touches 5 files plus the bot. Exact mapping confirmed via `src/engine/weapons.ts`: pistol = "echo pistol" (index 0), shotgun = "Regex Shotgun" (index 1) â€” **both currently draw from the same shared `"bullets"` pool**, smg = "gdb" (index 3, own `"smg"` pool), rocketlauncher = "ghidra" (index 4, own `"rockets"` pool).
   - **Key-binding collision found and resolved (user decision, 2026-07-16)**: `KeyR` was already "interact" (`src/engine/input.ts:538`, `consumeInteract()` â€” lore terminals, secret walls), and the note's own suggested fallback (`KeyF`) was already fullscreen toggle (`input.ts:558`). Resolved as a 3-way remap: **interact -> F, reload -> R, fullscreen -> Alt+Enter**. Alt+Enter is currently unbound in `input.ts` (no existing `"Enter"`/`altKey` handling to collide with) and matches genre/media-player convention for fullscreen. **Real risk, not yet verified**: this project already has a documented incident where a held-modifier binding (`Ctrl+W`) turned out to be an *unblockable OS/browser-level* reserved shortcut that no amount of synthetic-`KeyboardEvent` testing could catch â€” only real, manual keyboard input surfaced it. Alt+Enter carries the same class of risk (some window managers/browsers reserve it for their own fullscreen toggle, which could double-fire against this app's own `requestFullscreen()`/`exitFullscreen()` calls, or get eaten before reaching the page at all) â€” must be verified by an actual physical keypress in a real browser window before shipping, exactly like the Ctrl+W incident, not just added and trusted.
   - **No magazine concept exists anywhere today** â€” `src/engine/ammo.ts`'s `AmmoPools` is purely 4 flat reserve pools (`bullets`/`rockets`/`smg`/`gas`), consumed straight from the pool per shot in `engine.ts`'s `fire()` (`this.ammo[weapon.ammoType] -= weapon.ammoPerShot`). A "mag size" per the note's numbers would be a *new*, separate per-weapon "currently loaded" counter (reload = moves N rounds from the shared reserve pool into that counter, capped by both mag size and remaining reserve), not a restructuring of `AmmoPools` itself. Open question this raises directly: pistol and shotgun share the `"bullets"` reserve but would get *separate* mag counters (9 vs 2) under this design â€” confirm that's the intent (it reads as yes, given the note's own per-weapon mag sizes) rather than a shared mag.
   - **Fire-gating hook, precisely**: `engine.ts`'s `updateFiring(dt)` (~line 1795) is the single choke point for both the `auto` branch (`isFireHeld()`) and the semi-auto branch (`consumeFire()`) â€” a `reloading` flag checked at its top would block both uniformly. `fire()` (~line 1828) is where ammo is actually spent and where the "out of ammo" console log already lives â€” the auto-reload-when-empty trigger and the magazine-vs-reserve check both slot in here.
   - **Animation has no existing frame/sprite system to hook into** â€” `viewmodel.ts`'s `WeaponView` is procedurally hand-drawn per weapon (`drawPistol`/`drawShotgun`/`drawMp`/`drawRocketLauncher`, parameterized by a normalized `recoil`/`flash`, same idea `muzzleFrames`/`this.recoil = 1` already drive in `engine.ts`). A reload animation means new procedural motion added to each of those 4 draw functions specifically (e.g. a `reloadProgress` field on `WeaponView` the same shape as `recoil`), not just wiring an existing asset â€” real per-weapon animation-art work, not a mechanical hookup.
   - **SFX**: `audio.ts`'s `playShoot(kind: WeaponViewKind)` switches on `viewKind` to a per-weapon procedurally-synthesized sound (this project's audio is fully procedural, no sample files â€” see the audio-pitch memory). A `playReload(kind)` following the exact same dispatch shape is straightforward, but is 4 new procedurally-synthesized sounds (or one shared generic "reload clack" reused across weapons, cheaper but less distinct) â€” a design call, not just plumbing.
   - **Bot-side gap**: `scripts/run-balancing-telemetry.mjs`'s fire decision has zero concept of "weapon is currently reloading, don't hold fire / don't switch to it expecting an instant shot" â€” without new bot logic, the balancing bot would look broken (holding a dead trigger, or switching to a still-reloading weapon) the same class of issue the auto-fire bug this session already showed up as. Needs a `getPlayerState()` exposure of reload state (mirroring how `ammo`/`weaponIndex` are already exposed) before the bot can react to it sensibly, and would materially change weapon-choice timing (e.g. don't switch to gdb mid-fight if it just emptied a mag) â€” this alone is enough new bot-side work to warrant its own verification pass once implemented, not just "wire it and rerun `balancing:scan`."
 - [ ] reuse `telemetry.ts`/`getTelemetrySnapshot()` for a level-end player-facing stats screen â€” the recording infrastructure already accumulates most of what a "how'd I do" screen would want (kills, weapon accuracy, damage taken by source, time survived, loot collected), it's just currently gated behind `?testHooks=1` for the balancing bot only. Would need making telemetry recording unconditional (or a lighter always-on subset) and picking a curated player-facing slice â€” skip the bot/balance-only fields (TTK windows, forced-melee-kill count, mines triggered/disarmed).
